1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. exd4 Qb6!? { Qb6 is sometimes the
most annoying move a London player can face. In many cases it is awkward for
white to defend b2. In this case, white responds with a very powerful and
thematic move... } 6. Nc3! { Very typical idea-- preparing to meet Qxb2 with
Nb5 } 6... Bd7 { trying to prevent Nb5 and threatening Qxb2 } (6... Qxb2? 7. Nb5! $18 Na6 8. Rb1 Qxa2 9. Ra1 Qb2 10. Bd3 $18 { Too many issues for black... White
plans the simple 0-0, Qe2, and Rfb1. Of course, there also exist ideas of Rxa6
and Nc7 }) 7. Ne5! { Again, dealing with the threat on b2 with aggression
rather than passive defense } 7... a6 { fully preventing Nb5 and wanting to capture
on b2 } (7... Qxb2? 8. Nb5! Bxb5 9. Rb1 Qc3+ 10. Bd2 Qxd4 11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Rxb7+ Kc8 15. Rc7+ Kd8 16. O-O $18) 8. Qf3 e6 (8... Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qxc2 10. Rxb7 $16) 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. g4 Qa5 12. Kb1 { always play Kb1! } 12... b5 13. Bd3 b4 14. Ne2 Ne4?! (14... Qb6!? 15. g5 Ne4 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Qh3 $14 { [%cal Gg5g6] }) 15. Ng3! { one of the most
important moves of the game. Whites puts into question black's previous move.
Black now is to provoked to go "all in" on the queenside } 15... Nc3+ 16. bxc3 bxc3 17. Ka1 Ba3 18. Rb1 Bb2+ 19. Rxb2 cxb2+ { White to move. Take the pawn or Kb1? } 20. Kb1 O-O 21. g5 f5 (21... Rfb8 22. Qh5 g6 23. Qh6 { unstoppable threat of
Nh5! }) 22. gxf6 Rxf6 23. Nh5 Rf7 24. Rg1 Bb5 25. Nxg7 Rxg7 26. Rxg7+ Kxg7 27. Be5+ Kg8 { White to move mate in 3 } 28. Bxh7+ { 1-0 Black resigns. } (28. Kxh7 Qf7+ 29. Kh6 Bf4#) 1-0


